        'briefing_json' => [
            'en' => [
                'situation'           => 'You are the Master of a push convoy consisting of a push boat and two barges, total length 135 metres and beam 17 metres, loaded with 5,600 tonnes of coal at a combined draft of 3.8 metres. You are currently on the River Rhine near Mannheim, heading upstream. The water level at the Maxau gauge — the reference gauge for the Upper Rhine between Mannheim and Karlsruhe — is currently reading 740 cm and rising rapidly. The critical threshold is HSW II (Höchster Schifffahrtswasserstand II) at 820 cm at Maxau: when this level is reached, navigation is prohibited for loaded commercial vessels on this stretch of the Rhine. Based on the current rate of rise and the upstream rainfall data from the River Information Services (RIS), the water level is forecast to reach 820 cm within approximately 12 hours, giving you a narrowing operational window. Your destination is the coal-fired power plant at Karlsruhe, which is upstream from your current position. Under normal conditions, the transit from Mannheim to Karlsruhe takes approximately 3.5 hours. However, the current is now running at 10 to 12 km/h due to the high water, and your push convoy — which makes 16 km/h through the water in normal conditions — can only achieve 4 to 5 km/h over ground against this current. At this reduced speed, the transit to Karlsruhe will take approximately 6 hours. This means you would arrive at Karlsruhe with approximately 6 hours remaining before HSW II is reached — but this forecast is uncertain, and the water could rise faster than predicted. Bridge clearances are becoming critical: the Maxau road bridge, which you must pass under to reach Karlsruhe, has a published soffit height of approximately 8.0 metres above the reference water level. At the current 740 cm gauge reading, the actual clearance above the water surface is approximately 2.2 metres. Your convoy\'s highest fixed point is the push boat\'s radar mast at 6.8 metres above the waterline — but r