                    '4' => 'Thorough flood risk analysis: examines multiple gauge readings along the route (not just Maxau) to understand the flood wave progression, considers the lag time between upstream gauges and the Maxau reading — if upstream gauges are still rising sharply, the Maxau rise will accelerate, calculates the worst-case scenario: if the water rises to HSW II in 8 hours instead of 12 (33% faster than forecast), the convoy would be only 2/3 of the way to Karlsruhe with no safe berth options in the narrow section, monitors whether the WSA is preparing to issue a navigation closure (contact WSA directly for latest intelligence), assesses the secondary effects of high water — increased current means increased fuel consumption and engine stress, the convoy may make less than 4 km/h if the current increases further, recognizes that turning around becomes increasingly difficult for a 135m push convoy as the current strengthens.',
                    '5' => 'Expert flood stage management: integrates all available data sources for a comprehensive flood assessment — Maxau gauge (current and trend), upstream gauges (Plittersdorf, Kehl, Basel — each providing a leading indicator), RIS flood bulletins, weather radar for ongoing precipitation in the catchment, calculates multiple scenarios with different rise rates and determines the decision point for each (if water reaches X cm by time Y, must turn around at position Z), recognizes that the 12-hour forecast has significant uncertainty and builds safety margins accordingly — treats the available window as effectively 8-9 hours rather than 12, considers the non-linear nature of Rhine flooding (above certain levels, floodplain inundation slows the rise, but below those levels the confined channel causes faster rise), monitors for official WSA communications that may impose earlier restrictions than HSW II (some stretches may be closed earlier based on local conditions), factors in that at high water the river character changes — eddies, cross-currents, and unpredictable flow patterns develop near groynes and river structures, making navigation more hazardous even before the official closure.',
