                    '4' => 'Thorough convoy safety measures: monitors both engines continuously — at sustained high load (both engines at or near maximum to maintain 4-5 km/h over ground), the risk of mechanical failure increases, and losing one engine in this current would leave the convoy without sufficient power to maintain steerage, inspects coupling hardware and wire/chain tensions between push boat and barges at regular intervals, establishes a structured debris watch with the deckhand positioned forward on the lead barge with a radio, scanning the water and reporting objects, develops an avoidance protocol for large debris (immediate speed reduction and rudder action, but recognizes that the convoy\'s manoeuvrability at 4-5 km/h in strong current is very limited), manages crew fatigue — plans 2-hours-on, 2-hours-off rotation for the wheelhouse watch, but recognizes that with only 4 crew and one of them the Engineer (who must monitor engines), the rotation options are very limited, considers the psychological pressure on the crew of operating against the flood current with debris hazard.',
